{"text": "can expand \u03a8 \u221d\u03a8\u03b5e\u2212i\u03b5t, this reduces to the conventional BdG equation\n\n\u2212i\u03c32\u22021\u03a8 + m(x)\u03c33\u03a8 = \u03b5\u03a8,\n\n(54)\n\nwhere the charge conjugation constraint for the Majorana mode Eq. 10 is now equivalent\n\nto the particle-hole symmetry of BdG equations and maps energy eigenvalues of the above\n\n23\n\nequation from \u03b5 to \u2212\u03b5. Thus, the bulk quasiparticles in the p\u2212wave superconductor realize\n\na solid state analog of Majorana fermions19, exactly in the same way that semiconductors\n\nwith a massive Dirac dispersion realize Dirac fermions. Despite the BCS Hamiltonian being\n\ndiscovered more than fifty years ago, it was only recently pointed out that the Majorana na-\n\nture of such superconducting quasiparticleas can be tested by observing the pair annihilation\n\nof pairs of Bogoliubov quasiparticles71.\n\nLet us now discuss zero energy bound states localized in defects of the Majorana mass\n\nin Eq. 51 following the observation that Eq. 54 is formally identical to the Jackiw-Rebbi\n\nEq. 20.\n\nBecause of the correspondence between the Majorana equation Eq. 51 and the\n\np\u2212wave superconductors discussed above, such defects correspond to defects in the p\u2212wave\n\nsuperconductor Eq. 48 where one goes from \u0303\u03bc > 0 to \u0303\u03bc < 0 as x crosses 0. Interestingly,\n\nzero-energy modes were predicted in high-energy physics72 as bound states in vortices of\n\nscalar fields that are coupled to Dirac fermions.\n\nSince we are looking for bound states\n\nwithout momentum conservation, the appropriate Majorana field ansatz generalizing Eq. 12\n\nis written as\n\n\u03a8(x) = \u03a6(x)q\u03b5ei\u03b5t + q\u2020\n\n\u03b5e\u2212i\u03b5tC\u03a6\u2217(x),\n\n(55)\n\nwhere \u03a8(x) satisfies the Majorana equation Eq. 51 or equivalently the time-dependent BdG\n\nequation Eq. 53 if \u03a6(x) satisfies Eq. 20. As discussed in subsection II A, Eq. 20 has real\n\nsolution at \u03b5 = 0, \u03a6(x) = \u03c60(x), which satisfies Eq. 21, which is equivalent to the Majorana\n\ncondition Eq. 10 so that \u03a6(x) = C\u03a6\u2217(x).", "embedding": [0.0245554, -0.0064759543, 0.013647038, 0.040749233, 0.012048242, -0.018902877, 0.006905883, 0.004102835, -0.04398648, 0.07607531, 0.013219541, -0.016754575, 0.036811948, -0.040454496, -0.04636257, 0.0033048538, -0.022889877, -0.00921331, -0.09402481, 0.034656007, -0.007664537, 0.024277037, -0.03895622, -0.013262494, -0.01245751, 0.050785225, 0.0006755709, 0.042681158, 0.029111149, 0.014220179, 0.031863395, -0.018496932, 0.0016579728, -0.050389517, 0.017976092, 0.04583194, -0.007851807, -0.038099777, 0.040862028, -0.0026044506, 0.074329905, -0.007321381, -0.0028554227, -0.0110782925, -0.045093946, 0.008786852, -0.041203137, 0.01069375, -0.029401293, -0.081692204, 0.008193339, 0.013403236, 0.034822576, -0.0074708494, 0.014341377, -0.01132526, 0.0067756902, -0.0053649987, -0.032002408, -0.018950757, 0.009794259, -0.033011995, 0.008401088, -0.044777863, -0.008094108, 0.036168184, -0.011650369, 0.07148581, -0.005952194, -0.029097024, 0.0033769503, 0.00988769, 0.0041763317, 0.0072465157, -0.04723601, 0.027634805, 0.01993047, -0.057273947, -0.07954519, -0.02277821, -0.015964983, -0.014948536, -0.01580208, 0.013363286, -0.009626906, -0.030674957, -0.02828978, -0.03228131, -0.0024606772, 0.007824866, 0.00891613, 0.04792215, -0.04069878, 0.030846663, 0.060276784, 0.015996017, -0.010494789, 0.008386015, 0.036865506, 0.019217785, -0.019138694, 0.057499602, -0.042117853, 0.070972525, -0.036214687, 0.061998677, 0.005196724, 0.016455965, -0.000918095, -0.041628446, 0.039036997, 0.007671467, 0.015884215, 0.03918299, -0.0077985525, 0.03754405, 0.018239774, 0.005330531, -0.0436672, -0.037652686, -0.013011009, -0.0049331975, 0.06847662, 0.013571961, -0.026751963, -0.034001168, 0.009544703, 0.044388242, -0.016166983, 0.0037743524, 0.03444591, 0.017771788, 0.014770579, 0.04178229, -0.029922007, 0.020701103, -0.029145792,